        text: "Jack was driving home from a nightclub last one night when he came across a car which had gone off the road and collided with a tree. As the road was quite narrow and twisty, Jack stopped his car, put on his hazard flashers and went to see if there was anyone hurt. Inside the vehicle he saw Diane unconscious at the wheel, there was blood over her face. Jack quickly felt for Diane's pulse and noticed that in addition to a strong heartbeat, her breathing seemed regular and strong. Jack got his mobile phone and tried to call 999 but there was no reception. Jack was now beginning to panic. He was frightened that another car might come along and crash into his car. Jack was also a first year medical student and he remembered a recent lecture indicating that most trauma victims fully recover from their injuries if they receive medical treatment within half an hour of the trauma event. Jack now decided to act swiftly. He carefully lifted Diane out of the vehicle and carried her to his car. He gently turned his car around and headed off to the local hospital. Arriving at the Accident and Emergency he noticed that it was in the darkness. He quickly saw the sign that due to cutbacks this A & E was closed after 8pm each night and directing people to a different hospital ten miles in the opposite direction, back the way he had come. Jack headed back eventually arriving at the A & E department. The doctors examined Diane and found that what would have been moderate injuries from the accident had been exacerbated by either Diane's removal from the scene of the accident without proper neck support or the extended drive to the hospital. Diane is now unable to move her body from her neck down. Advise Jack as to any potential liability in tort he might owe Diane.",
