        text: 'The Hillclimber is a large 4 wheel drive (4WD or AWD) SUV made by Caprica Motors Ltd., and which is normally sold to farmers and other people who engage in serious off road driving. However, it has become somewhat of a status symbol for city drivers and Caprica Motors have brought out a cheaper two wheel drive version (2WD). Bill recently purchased a new two wheel drive Hillclimber, although he knows nothing about cars. Bill read the manual which said that "in icy or snowy conditions, press the switch marked AWD to activate drive to all four wheels for secure effortless and safe driving in any condition." Bill glanced down at the at the bottom of the page where it stated "Does not apply to 2WD variants. Always exercise caution when driving in adverse conditions." But had no idea what 2WD meant so ignored it. All 2WD vehicles had the AWD switch but it served no purpose. It was retained simply to save costs. Caprica Motors instructed local dealers to place a warning sticker next to the AWD switch. The sticker on Bill\'s car consisted of 4WD in red letters, surrounded by a red circle with a red line going through it. Bill had seen this warning sticker but did not understand the letters 4WD. One day in early January, Bill came across a line of cars unable to go up a hill due to icy conditions. Switching on the AWD, he accelerated past them, driving smoothly up the hill. Suddenly he lost control on the ice and spun out, damaging several cars before sliding back down the hill where he slammed into a wall. Bill believes that the Hillclimber did not operate as it should have. Advise Bill as to whether the Caprica Motors owe any liability in tort under statute.',
