        text: 'Lee was on holiday, enjoying the pleasures of Apollo Lake, a small lake in the midlands, often used by tourists for many water sports activities, such as waterskiing and so forth. Lee himself used a jet ski. Late one evening, he decided to have a moonlight ride on the jet-ski with his girlfriend, Deirdre. As they were enjoying themselves, the jet-ski suddenly stopped. No matter what Lee did, he could not restart the jet-ski. Realising that there was no one else on the lake and that they could not stay there for much longer before feeling the impact of hypothermia, Lee and Deirdre began to swim to the nearest shoreline. Once they were on dry land, Lee quickly realised that he had no idea where they were, but they were definitely far away from where they parked their car. Accordingly, Lee felt that they should head inland and try to find any house where they parked their car. Accordingly, Lee felt that they should head inland and try to find any house where they could make a phone call for help. Lee and Deirdre crossed a number of hedgerows and fences without too much difficulty before encountering a long, high wall which blocked their path. As there was no way around the wall, Lee and Deirdre climbed over it with great difficulty, Lee cutting his arm in the process from where some shards of broken glass had been embedded on the top of the wall. Bleeding profusely, both Lee and Deirdre began running as fast as possible when they could hear the sound of some dogs barking coming towards them at speed. In the pitch black, and seized with fear from the dogs which appeared to be drawing very close, Lee was grateful for the relatively smooth terrain compared to the other fields that they had encountered. Suddenly Deirdre screamed as she fell into what appeared to be a hole in the ground and broke her leg. Meanwhile the dogs had caught up with Lee and one had bitten him before his handler called him off. Lee discovered that they had wandered onto the local golf course and that Deirdre had fallen into a bunker. Advise Lee and Deirdre as to any tort claim they might have against the owners of the golf course.',
