        text: 'John owned a large motorcycle that he enjoyed riding on the remote roads in Connemara. He meticulously maintained the motorcycle as it was his pride and joy. One day, John decided that he would do a tour of the country, staying in campsites overnight and moving on the next day, living the nomadic life he had been attracted to when watching television shows. He loaded up the motorcycle with a small tent and enough clothing and other supplies to keep him for about three weeks. It was a struggle to get everything packed onto the motorcycle, but he managed. When his friend Jane heard what he was doing, she insisted that she come along as well. John did not really want her to do so, but Jane was insistent and John relented saying to her: "OK, but you will have to look after yourself. And you cannot take much with you, the bike is already well loaded with my stuff." Jane agreed but found that there were so many things that she needed, it was difficult to leave anything behind. John and Jane were getting on exceptionally well, and John decided that he would show off to Jane and began to overtake a vehicle on a back road doing over 120km/h. As John passed the vehicle, the bike began to wobble and John lost control, resulting in Jane being thrown from the motorcycle resulting in severe injury. The evidence shows that John was speeding and that the bike was overloaded. However, the evidence also showed that unknown to anyone, the rear tyre had a slow puncture from an embedded nail and that this would ultimately have produced a similar wobble in the ordinary use of the motorcycle resulting in a loss of control of the motorcycle. Advise John as to whether he is the cause of any harm to Jane under the law of tort.',
