        text: "Billy owns a public house in a small village in the countryside. For a variety of reasons his clientele has been steadily shrinking, So much so that he knows virtually all his regular clients by name. In an attempt to increase business in the pub, Billy has run a Valentine's Night event. Essentially, whenever someone buys a drink, they will get another drink of the same value free if they can show they are celebrating Valentine's night with a loved one. Word spreads through the town like wildfire and on Valentine's night Billy's pub is packed. Billy is taken aback. He had thought that the offer would be popular but had not anticipated the sheer numbers of people involved. Overwhelmed, Billy does not bother checking whether any individual ordering a drink has a date but simply puts up two drinks for every order received. He also does the same for Larry, a regular who is at the pub every night. By the end of the evening, Billy is exhausted and Larry is completely inebriated. As Billy begins clearing the pub, Larry asks if he can stay the night as he does not feel that he is in a fit condition to drive home. Billy is taken aback, and says \"Go on a way out of that, you're grand. You cannot stay here, that's for sure.\" As Larry gets up, he stumbles to the floor and again asks Billy if he can stay. Billy says \"Sure listen, it's only a couple of miles, you'll be grand.\" Larry asks Billy to keep his car keys until the morning as he says that he doesn't trust himself to drive, but Billy does not want the responsibility and says \"If you are able to know that you shouldn't drive, you are not likely to drive, now are you.\" Larry replies with \"I suppose that's true!\" Larry loses control on the drive home and is severely injured. Advise Billy if he owes Larry a duty of care under the law of tort.",
