        text: 'Global Remedy manufactures various medical devices, particularly in the field of nicotine addiction. They have been in business for the last twenty years and have proven to be very successful, with an extensive domestic and export market. One of their most successful products is a small bio-degradable plastic device which is implanted under the skin and which emits a slow release nicotine substitute, allowing the patient to break their addiction to smoking. Global Remedy does not actually manufacture this product but in fact assembles the component parts from two suppliers: the pharmaceutical company which supplies the actual medication and the manufacturer which makes the bio-degradable plastic container. Global Remedy has recently been informed by the supplier of the bio-degradable plastic element that there may be an issue with the quality of the plastic that could result in it disintegrating. If that were the case, the effect would be to release all the medication in one go which might cause complications for the patient. Unfortunately there is no way of determining if the plastic element of any particular container is defective without removing it for inspection. Jill had been trying to quit smoking for years and finally had one of these devices implanted into her arm. One day while surfing on the internet, she came across various sites which alleged that Global Remedy was trying to cover up that these devices were dangerous. Jill now wants the device removed immediately, although there is no evidence that it has malfunctioned. Advise Jill as whether she has any action in tort against the manufacturer of the device.',
