          'Jen operates an advice and support centre that helps small businesses in… Frustrat.',
        text: "Jen operates an advice and support centre that helps small businesses in pursuing claims for non-payment of debts. Over the years she has become increasingly frustrated with the attitude of people with regard to paying her clients what they are owed. As a result, in recent times, she has taken to putting up posters in the front window of the centre which contain pictures and details of individuals who have been forced to court to pay the debts owed to her clients. On the posters she has a large color picture of the individual, with the words PAY YOUR DEBTS, SCUMBAG! Below in smaller print there is more detail about the amount of money owed, to whom and for how long. Jen calls it the window of infamy. One of Jen's clients has accused Douglas of not paying what he owes to them. Douglas has disputed this, saying that he transferred the money electronically, although he admits that he may have provided incorrect bank details for Jen's client but that his bank has said it may take some time to establish where the money has gone to, if they are ever able to find out. Douglas has refused to deal with the issue, saying it is for the bank to sort out. Jen decides to post Douglas' picture in her window of infamy. One day, National Television is filming a piece on the impact of the pandemic for the evening news that night. When it is broadcast, the front of Jen's centre is clearly visible and in particular the picture of Douglas with PAY YOUR DEBTS, SCUMBAG! is clearly visible. Advise Douglas if he has any action in tort law only against either Jen or National Television.",
